pages: Title: Making diversity and inclusion relevant for undergraduate Computer Science students, and making them want more Abstract: This workshop involves attendees to demonstrate models, tools, and methods used to guide undergraduate computer science (CS) students to identify and propose systemic solutions for inclusion, diversity and social justice problems that occur in CS education, professions, and products. This is based on systemic theories of justice, and practices of organizational change. Students identify this as valuable and also indicate they would welcome more of the same in future CS courses. ----- Outline of the session Title: Making diversity and inclusion relevant for undergraduate Computer Science students, and making them want more FName, LName: Donald Winiecki 15 minutes: Introduction including (a) description of theoretical background supporting choice of methods, media, materials, (b) learner analysis, and (c) how anti-racism, anti-paternalism, are incorporated into the methods, media, and materials 60 minutes: Interactive demonstration of the lesson plan (attached, "CS-HU130 Case Example - A Colorful Situation.pdf"), including: (a) source material for this case example, (b) regular insertion of meta-analytic comments underpinning particular passages, and (c) strategies for addressing different kinds of comments commonly offered by students, 15 minutes: Review of documentation of effects of the course, including (a) evaluation survey used at the end of the course (b) how to weave strategies into other courses ~ 90 minute Annual Conference Workshop FName: Donald LName: Winiecki Preferred Suffix: PhD, EdD Job title: Professor of Ethics & Morality in Professional Practice Organization: Boise State University, College of Engineering Address, City, State, Zip: 1910 University DR // Boise, Idaho 83925-2070 Phone: 2085718096 Biography: Donald Winiecki is Professor of Ethics & Morality in Professional Practice (PEMPP) in the Boise State University, College of Engineering. He holds a Doctor of Education degree in Instructional Technology (Texas Tech University) and a Doctor of Philosophy degree in Sociology (Central Queensland University). He teaches graduate courses in Professional Ethics to students studying “Organizational Performance & Workplace Learning” and undergraduate courses in Foundational Values to “Computer Science” students, and is a regular guest presenter in professional ethics and professional morality across curricula in the College of Engineering at Boise State University. He has actively published and presented empirical research and case studies since 1996. LinkedIn: https://www.linkedin.com/in/don-winiecki-a1b23918/ Twitter: na Facebook: https://www.facebook.com/BoiseStateOPWL Second Presenter: no Title: Making diversity and inclusion relevant for undergraduate Computer Science students, and making them want more Topical focus: Specific Ethnic/Racial Population(s), Gender, LGBTQIA+, Individuals with Disabilities, Intersectionality, Adult learners Intended audience: Faculty members responsible for teaching and research related to the ethics and morality of conduct and solving problems related to conduct in STEM-focused learning and working environments. Abstract: This workshop involves attendees to demonstrate models, tools, and methods used to guide undergraduate computer science (CS) students to identify and propose systemic solutions for inclusion, diversity and social justice problems that occur in CS education, professions, and products. This is based on systemic theories of justice, and practices of organizational change. Students identify this as valuable and also indicate they would welcome more of the same in future CS courses. Learning Objectives: Attendees will be able to: 1. name and describe principal barriers to inclusion that exist in undergraduate STEM-oriented classrooms. 2. name and describe elements of theories of justice and processes of organizational change that can be used to address issues of inclusion, diversity, and justice in STEM-oriented classrooms and professional practice. 3. analyze and suggest systemic solutions to address issues of inclusion, diversity, and justice in STEM-oriented classrooms and professional practice. Description: Introduction: Within the context of an NSF-funded RED project (Revolutionizing Engineering and Computer Science Departments) focused on replicating the best elements of a successful technology company within undergraduate higher education (our "CSP-Hatchery"), we have embedded a set of 1-credit courses within the normal curricula. These courses include electives addressing currently emerging technical skills required by industry, and also include a focus on responding to corporate interests in improving inclusion, diversity, and justice in STEM education (particularly, computer science) and technology work and as influenced by technologies in society. This workshop focuses on theory, methods, media, and classroom management of a 1-credit course in "Foundational Values" required of all incoming students in the Computer Science (CS) undergraduate degree at Boise State University. The presenter is the designer and faculty lead on delivery of this course. This workshop provides a multi-perspective view on this course. First, it reviews the instructional technology underpinning its design and delivery, including learner analysis and selection of media and methods. Second, it involves the audience in a demonstration of the principal activity used in the course. Third, in the process of this interactive demonstration, it provides meta-analytic perspectives that guide instructional methods as they often play out in the course with different kinds of students. In this way, this workshop provides timely and relevant information for immediate application by attendees. Attendees at this workshop will receive a complete lesson plan and instructional materials for the activity addressed. Finally, this workshop will report student outcomes compiled from three consecutive years of delivery of this course. The Problem: Social science and a growing archive of literature and activism provides substantial resources for those aiming to address gaps in knowledge and understanding related to injustices in our society. However, those injustices persist and may even be expanding in scope and depth as we discover more about physical, administrative, technical, and personal practices reflect and enforce biases. As educators of undergraduate students, we are severely challenged to address structural changes across the whole span of events, but we are perfectly positioned to help our students develop perspectives and skills that can help them address some of these issues no matter where they find themselves. This possibility nominates each of us as part of a system of beneficial change. Because we are part of the system of higher education we can take advantage of other efforts in our schools, colleges, and universities, and add curricula that channels those other efforts to make them especially powerful for our students in their technical and future vocational pursuits. Those other efforts often come from departments in other colleges -- sociology, history, philosophy, and others -- with courses that document and analyze social problems and provide strong theory and advice on how to address those problems. There are also progressive efforts to address issues related to "algorithmic bias," structural access/inaccess to technologies, and more within the fields of computer science and engineering, but they are -- so far -- not a part of the central curricular and professional focus, and they remain mostly isolated in individual elective courses without systemic influence. Additionally, however powerful they may be, curricula in other academic departments may not focus on specific phenomena they believe to be relevant in their technical pursuits, or which meet our students "where they are" in their lives. While some students reflect a general acceptance of these societal problems, they don't often see a path that links this to their chosen technical career, especially when their course curricula put a nearly exclusive focus on technical knowledge and skills. These are the individuals who justify inaction on the point that "it's not my problem." Other students tell us that these courses are explicitly not relevant to them or that they only serve to bolster the university's perceived role to "indoctrinate them" into a particular social agenda or political viewpoint. These individuals point to the nearly entirely technical curricula before them to justify that anything other than technical knowledge and skill is irrelevant, or stand on an already-existing and strongly held belief -- bolstered in phenomena reported in the popular press -- that a worldview of inclusion, diversity, and justice is (to them) actually a worldview that explicitly hurts them. All of these viewpoints also reflect a couplet of facts which underpin the whole of all issues related to inclusion, diversity, and justice in our society -- the majority of individuals who enter our classrooms and who populate technology workplaces are white or Asian males, and the majority of instances where inclusion, diversity, and justice are lost in our society involve individuals who are underrepresented in our classrooms and in workplaces are not members of these groups. This means the people we are attempting to guide may not have personal experiences of systemic and persistent loss of inclusion, diversity, and justice. This inexperience allows the majority to deny that such issues exist because they have not felt them. In other words, we as educators face multiple sources and sorts of resistance, possibly grounded in gaps in experiences, to efforts aiming to address these issues. This points to a need to reduce resistance to change at the same time -- or even before -- we might begin more dedicated moves toward making change. It also alludes to possible instructional methods we can use to provide some level of experience that highlights the authenticity of these problems, and which in turn can open the door to action. To review, in all of the identified sorts of resistance suggested above, two things stand out. First, each of them starts with a pre-existing attitude that our efforts are (a) beside the point, (b) irrelevant, or even (c) a danger to their success in a technical career. Second, each of them can be seen to be related to a lack of relevant personal experience with the issues. Constraints, Resources, and our Intervention: It will not be a surprise to note additional difficulties encountered with attempts to add new content and courses to an existing undergraduate degree in CS. Within our RED project we modified the existing undergraduate curricula to require a flexible set of 5, 1-credit "Hatchery unit" courses in every student's degree plan. One of these courses, CS-HU 130 "Foundational Values," is required of every incoming student. This course is restricted to only 12.5 contact hours across 5 weeks and 10, 75 minute sessions. Since the project began in 2017 enrollment in this course had been capped at 30. After moving the course to an online format for Fall 2020 and in response to strong demand due to COVID-19, we have raised the cap to 50. Review of related literature and interviews with industry representatives indicated that all software development companies organize their personnel in teams -- there are effectively no instances where sole-developers complete a commercial project of any size. This points to the use of teamwork in the course process so we can leverage that experience as an early step toward the Hatchery goals overall. workshop reports on and engages attendees Severe restrictions on time -- a 1-credit, 5-week course (12.5 contact hours) Dale's cone of experience -- vicarious experiences through case studies Framed from the standpoint of how skills in addressing IDJ problems can improve their chances of success (teamwork, reproducible rubrics, repeated and varied practice)

work_title: From Faulkner to Fake News: Building Bridges between Literary and Digital Reading
pages: Chapter 1: Introduction (submitted) Chapter 2: Fake News: What it is, why it’s important, and why it works. This chapter discusses the difference among misinformation, disinformation, and malinformation and why search algorithms may lead to confirmation bias. The chapter includes analysis of the unique features of born digital texts. The accompanying lessons will focus on helping students recognize their areas of susceptibility, helping them develop an ethic of responsibility in reading and posting, and encouraging lateral reading Chapter 3: When Choosing texts and designing units Chapter 3: When teaching close reading This chapter will focus on transferring understanding about the close reading of linear texts to the close reading of digital texts, using rules of notice as a heuristic. Rules of notice are the conventional understandings experienced readers employ when they engage with texts to apportion their attention. More specifically, the lessons will introduce students to the importance of noticing direct statements of generalization, calls to attention, ruptures, and language designed to evoke a reader’s response and engage them in developing and applying rules of digital notice. Chapter 4: When teaching point of view (submitted) Chapter 5: When teaching critical theory This chapter will focus on the power of using critical lenses as a tool for understanding both literary and digital texts. More specifically, the chapter will focus on how the gender and social class lenses can enliven the discussion of literary texts and provide the grounds Chapter 6: When teaching argumentative writing This chapter will focus on helping students assess both linear and digital arguments and on developing understandings about how to mine digital sources in their argumentative writing. More specifically, lessons will focus on developing criteria for evidence that can be used as a safe starting point for arguments and on identifying the tacit and explicit reasoning that writers of digital texts use in connecting their evidence to their claims. Chapter 7: When teaching narrative writing This chapter will focus on helping students understand the way narratives are employed in digital texts and developing strategies for composing compelling personal narratives. The lessons will also examine the costs and benefits of different ways of sharing personal narratives in on-line environments. Chapter 8: When thinking about sensible sequencing and unit design This chapter will provide the mental model of EMPOWER (Envision, Map, Prime, Orient, Walkthrough, Extend/Explore, Reflect) which captures major implications for teaching from across the learning science

work_title: “Pushing the Boundaries of the Cloister: Alternative Monastic Practices in Post- Reformation England"
pages: After Henry VIII shut down Catholic religious houses following his break with Rome in 1534, few Catholic monasteries remained in England. Despite the dissolution, some Protestants, including Elizabeth I, feared that Catholics were forming monasteries illegally, just beyond the eyes of authorities. In reality, Catholics did continue many monastic practices in community with one another within England, especially within homes and prisons. With infrequent access to the typical conduits of grace—priests, sacraments, churches, and rituals—following Protestant reforms, Catholics feared for their salvation. The Catholic Church had maintained for centuries that the monastic path was the lifestyle most pleasing to God, so Catholics tried to recreate it. Without resources, rituals, and any significant Catholic institutional presence, however, these could not be monasteries in the usual sense. Motivated by religious need, Catholics borrowed from monastic traditions and combined them with whatever lay resources remained. The results were innovative communal practices that stretched the traditional boundaries between monastic and lay Catholic life. And while both men and women adopted such practices, gender norms helped determine which options were more attractive and available to members of each sex. This article explores the accommodations to monastic practice made by better-known Catholics working within England, such as Mary Ward, Luisa de Carvajal, Margaret Clitheroe, and William Weston, and modifications of lesser-known advocates, such as Elizabeth Cellier, Alexander MacKenzie, and Henry Tasburgh, to illuminate quasi-monastic communities and practices that vary in form but not in intent. Although motivated by need, these adaptations became normalized and spread beyond the boundaries of England, in the almost 300 years that Catholicism was illegal in the British Isles. Certain innovations, such as the Congregatio Jesu and the Institute of the Blessed Virgin Mary, exist worldwide today. Catholics remained connected to their past at the same time they broke with it. And by their own new paths, they forged connections to the past and future of Catholicism.

Community of Peace: Performing Geographies of Ecological Dignity in Colombia
pages: For two decades, a rural “peace community” in San José de Apartadó has resisted armed conflict in Urabá, one of Colombia’s most war-torn regions. Resisting land grabbing by entrepreneurs tied to drug trafficking, agribusiness, or mining, the Peace Community refuses to support paramilitaries, army soldiers, and guerrillas. Based on ethnographic action research over a twelve year period, Christopher Courtheyn illuminates the community’s understandings of peace and territorial practices against ongoing assassinations and forced displacement. Researched during Colombia’s peace process between the government and FARC guerrillas, Community of Peace illuminates grassroots peacebuilding. Through geographical performances with the dead, the land, and fellow resistance communities, San José creates a radical and relational peace of ecological dignity. Courtheyn intervenes into debates about the meaning of peace and territory, while also interrogating the role of race in Colombia’s war and the relationship between memory and peace. Amid the widespread violence of today’s global crisis, Community of Peace illustrates San José’s rupture with the logics of coloniality and capitalism through the construction of political solidarity and communal peace.

work_title: The Routledge Handbook of Critical Resource Geography
pages: How do conflicts around nature influence our attempts to learn about them? We use a dialogic approach to wrestle with this question drawing from our experience of working with movements against extractivism in Pakistan and Colombia. Resource geographies are constituted by embodied spatial practices, and social movements are rich sites of knowledge creation that can follow alternative epistemologies. Instead of considering social movements as objects of investigation, we focus on our own positionality, the performance of academic learning, and the embodied and performative aspects of these struggles that may contradict and even potentiate our modalities of learning about these conflicts. To do so, we explore action research and radical performance geography as approaches for doing critical resource geographies. This dialogue centers around a set of questions on the ethics, modalities, tools, and outputs of action research that lies at the intersection of political action and investigation.

work_title: Colombian peace communities resist citizen security, while protective accompaniment subverts democratic security: Reflections on racialized security
pages: This article offers a racial analysis of security in Colombia. I describe the racist underpinnings of government ‘citizen security’ and ‘democratic security’ projects by highlighting a rural peace community’s cross ethnic solidarity network against militarization. I also analyze the racial and colonial dimensions of Colombian peace communities’ use of unarmed international accompaniers as protection from attacks. As such, resistance to insecurity is a window into complex processes of racialization, toward conceptual critiques of security and anti-racist security methodologies.

work_title: Urban complexity, sustainability and policymaking
pages: The path towards the long-term prosperity of our species passes through the sustainability of urban environments. A transition to sustainability has to take place within socioecological complex adaptive systems. Thus, policy-making for urban sustainability in the 21st century requires that we seriously consider the relevance of a complex adaptive systems approach. This paper offers a new roadmap for policymakers operating in the space of urban sustainability. Firstly, we attempt to clarify how complexity science can have practical relevance sustainability policies through our understanding of emergent phenomena and employ a small-N comparative analysis of case studies. Secondly, we discuss various challenges that complexity places on policy-making, focusing on the concepts of predictive capacity, causal explanation, the unconscious mind and the erosion of moral sentiments; we argue that the synthesis of these ideas provides a more nuanced and useful view for policy-making in the urban sustainability context.

Overseas Troop Deployments, Extended Deterrence, and Asymmetric Conflict.”
pages: In the rationalist tradition, asymmetric intrastate conflict should not occur as the outcome is obvious ex ante and states can achieve a better bargain instead of paying the costs of war. However, asymmetric inter-state conflict does occur. This incongruity suggests a double-information problem regarding the intent, resolve, and capability of both minor and major powers in dispute. This manuscript suggests that large U.S. troop deployments create a unique solution to this problem by bridging information gaps for both states that have similar and dissimilar interests thereby provoking fewer opportunities for conflict. This paper combines research on asymmetric conflict, extended deterrence, and troop deployments to ascertain how U.S. security commitments affect conflict initiation in asymmetric relationships.

work_title: Playing Politics with War: Election Timing and Opposition Party Position Taking on the Use of Force
pages: Opposition party position taking on conflict initiation is an important motivator for both formal models of war and in explaining the causal process of the democratic peace. Most notably, Shultz (1998; 2001) shows that the opposition party can serve as a powerful signal to adversaries about state resolve and intent. We argue that the model does not hold up to traditional understandings of opposition party behavior. Instead, we suggest that the opposition party’s decision to support or oppose a war is a partly a function of election proximity. As an election nears, opposition parties have stronger incentives to support a budding conflict rather than oppose it. We test this hypothesis using force initiation votes in United States Senate and show that the staggered election cycle of the Senate produces different stimuli for legislators voting on the use of force.

work_title: Classifying Permutations under Context-Directed Swaps and the CDS Game
pages: A special sorting operation called Context Directed Swap, and denoted cds, involves block interchanges of permuted lists. In biology literature cds is hypothesized to be performed on the genomic material of ciliates. Among those permutations which are sortable by cds, cds sorts them using the fewest possible block interchanges of any kind. Adamyk et al. (2013) discovered an efficient way of quantifying the non-cds-sortability of a permutation by means of an object called the strategic pile of the permutation. We partially classify the permutations with maximal strategic pile by their number of available cds moves. We complete this characterization when the number of available moves is close to maximal as well as when the number of available moves is minimal.We discover a Zn × Zn-action on permutations in Sn+1 that preserves the number of available cds moves. Using the orbit-stabilizer theorem, we obtain some enumerative results regarding the number of permutations with maximal strategic pile and a given number of moves mod (2n−1)2.We also discover new conditions for player ONE to have a winning strategy in a two-person game played on non-cds-sortable permutations, improving results from Adamyk et al. (2013).

work_title: Characteristics influencing teacher intervention in bullying situations: a study in Idaho elementary schools
EDUCATION PROFESSIONALS’ KNOWLEDGE AND NEEDS REGARDING BULLYING
pages: https://youtu.be/9xC8KmiU4oI The purpose of this study was to analyze teachers' and other education professionals' needs and knowledge when dealing with bullying situations. Data collection was carried out in two different sessions of a bullying prevention one-day symposium at a four-year state university. The participants were 53 educational professionals from several elementary and middle schools. Qualitative analysis of session artifacts revealed that participants had a basic understanding of bullying; however, they doubt its definition and how to identify when it occurs. Participants in the case study were interested in being change agents when it comes to addressing bullying problems. However, they lacked self-confidence and access to appropriate resources to overcome their fears and lack of self- efficacy for proper intervention.

work_title: Effects of Ca doping on structural and optical properties of PZT nanopowders
pages: The influence of the addition of calcium ions (Ca2+) in the Pb(1-x)CaxZr0.52Ti0.48O3 system (PCZT) for x = 0.05, 0.10, 0.15, 0.20, and 0.25 on the structural and optical properties was systematically studied. The compositions were synthesized through a polymerized-complex approach based on the Pechini polymeric precursor route. The solubility limit of calcium ions within the PCZT lattice is in between x = 0.10 and x = 0.15, at which a CaTiO3 secondary phase is detected. The Goldschmidt tolerance factors, modified tolerance factors, and the effective vacancy sizes were all estimated for the synthesized nanopowders. While the Goldschmidt tolerance factors suggest the formation of a distorted perovskite structure, the values of the modified tolerance factor were extremely close to unity, indicating a strong stable ferroelectric perovskite structure. The optical band gap was found to decrease with calcium concentration to a minimum at x = 0.20 and then slightly increase at x = 0.25.

Articulating Effective Middle Grades Instructional Practices in A Teacher-Researcher Alliance
pages: One of the most intransigent problems in mathematics education is the culturally-influenced divide between classroom practice and educational research. This paper describes our explicit attempt to bridge that divide by translating research on instructional practices linked to improving students’ mathematics achievement into a brief guide outlining constructs, features, strategies, routines, and tools for use in a teacher-researcher alliance. We outline the design and development process, share the guide itself, and summarize data addressing the utility of the guide for a research and professional development project in which 100 U.S. Grades 6-8 teachers are collaborating to improve middle grades modeling and problem solving achievement.

work_title: Using Literature to Engage Students Mathematically
pages: In this article, the authors share two lessons that incorporate children’s literature with the Pythagorean theorem and area to engage preservice teachers (PSTs) mathematically. Sample responses, example texts, and future work are discussed.

work_title: Secondary Mathematics Teachers’ Planned Approaches for Teaching Standard Deviation
pages: Research-based guidelines for learning variation exist (e.g., Franklin et al., 2007; Garfield, delMas, & Chance, 2007), but little is known about how teachers plan to teach standard deviation, or how these plans align with recent recommendations. In this article, we survey lesson plans designed by inservice and preservice secondary mathematical teachers. We report on the accuracy, technology usage, and visual representations in the lesson plans. We consider how many elements are used, the level of conceptual development, and the mathematical nature. Findings support differences between preservice and master’s level students in education, as well as a tendency by in-service teachers to teach in alignment with prior learning experiences, despite professional development. Implications for teacher education and curricular development are offered.

Feeling - Emotion - Mood. Phenomenological and pedagogical perspectives
pages: Heidegger asserts that Stimmungen, sustained moods or attunements, are the fundamental mode or medium of our being and being‐together. In this sense Stimmungen can be said to fundamentally atmospheric. It is a shared mood or atmosphere that determines the way that the world is disclosed to us—meaning that atmospheres possess a deeply epistemic, hermeneutic dimension. If every atmosphere brings with it a shared interpretation of the world, then one needs to share or participate in this atmosphere in order to share in knowledge or learning. Only when a Stimmung suitable to such disclosure has been cultivated or encountered will the sought‐after knowledge “dawn” on one, as Bollnow puts it (2017, p. 1414; 1956, p. 57). It goes without saying that Bollnow’s statement has significant implications for pedagogy, for teaching and learning as fundamentally atmospheric experiences, and these are explored in this paper. But I begin by discussing the elusive epistemology of the atmospheric itself—what we are able to know about how we know, what access we have to the atmospheric, to the mode of our being and knowing. Then, through an illustrative video example, I go on to discuss what can be seen to make an atmosphere, a shared way of knowing, specifically pedagogical.

work_title: Companion to Herman Melville
pages: The growth and dispersal of Melville’s library and the roles of books and reading in his intellectual and creative experience have occupied a prominent place in Melville scholarship since the pioneering work of Merton M. Sealts, Jr., from the 1940s through the 1990s, and of Wilson Walker Cowen in the 1960s. In the present century, the work of tracking and documenting the recovery of Melville’s books, and of electronically editing his marginalia in surviving volumes, is carried on at Melville’s Marginalia Online. Whereas many important volumes owned by Melville remain lost, copies marked and annotated in his hand continue to resurface, with sporadic impacts of new evidence on scholarship devoted to this thought and craft. Current advancements in digital technology assist and expand our comprehension of old and new evidence, offering significant opportunities for the study of Melville’s reading life.

work_title: The Ghost of Okuma
pages: In The Ghosts of Okuma, a lonely teenager from San Diego searches the streets of Tokyo for his runaway sister. The young American soon befriends a mysterious but charismatic Fukushima refugee, who agrees to help him track down his sister in exchange for joining her solo crusade against nuclear power. What the unlikely pair discover leads them north to the abandoned towns and graveyards of the exclusion zone, where across this strange and ghostly landscape they rush headlong toward their ultimate act of rebellion: recording a protest video at the ruins of Fukushima Daiichi.

work_title: Industrial Apocalyptic: Neoliberalism, Coal, and the Burlesque Frame
pages: Rhetorical scholarship and cultural commentary have demonstrated that environmentalist voices are consistently associated with apocalyptic rhetoric. However, this association deflects attention from the apocalyptic rhetoric that comes from industry and countermovements to environmentalism. This essay seeks to remedy that oversight by proposing the concept of “industrial apocalyptic” as a significant rhetorical form in environmental controversy. Based on analysis of the rhetoric of the U.S. coal industry, we find that these industrial apocalyptic narratives rely on a burlesque frame to disrupt the categories of establishment and outsider and thus thwart environmental regulation. Ultimately, we argue that industrial apocalyptic co-opts environmentalist appeals for radical change in the service of blocking such change and naturalizes neoliberal ideology as the commonsense discourse of the center.

work_title: Eliciting Dispositions for Teaching in the Context of a Video-Based Intervention for Secondary Teacher Candidates
pages: For years, teacher education programs have focused considerable effort on teacher knowledge and how to develop the types of knowledge that matter in teacher education candidates. Meanwhile, candidate dispositions for teaching have received little attention, particularly in mathematics courses for candidates. As developers and practitioners of a curriculum intervention designed to support candidates’ mathematical knowledge, we are beginning to see how much disposition towards teaching mathematics matters in a candidate's ability to attend to students' ideas. In this paper we share results from a pilot study investigating the dispositional characteristics elicited in an online video-based curriculum focused on students’ ideas on a figural pattern task. Results indicate that efforts to cultivate secondary candidates' disposition for teaching may have payoffs with respect to both dispositions and knowledge.

Understanding the Persuasive Nature of Algorithms Through the Procedural Enthymeme
pages: Procedure, when discussed in regards to rhetoric, is framed overwhelmingly, if not exclusively, in regards to game play (and to video games most frequently). We argue that this view needs to be expanded if we are to realize how complex human-computer rhetor systems function rhetorically in diverse contexts. Such systems do so algorithmically through procedural enthymemes, which persuade audience agents to action through the apparent logic of a given system. Procedural persuasion occurs most often via strategies that facilitate the agent to assume an active role in “self-persuasion” in order to complete a given enthymeme. In this text, we explore the procedural enthymeme as a rhetorical tactic for human and nonhuman persuasion by looking at three case studies of commonly used technological “matching” systems—search engines (Google), online matchmaking (Match.com), and social networking (Facebook)—that employ procedural enthymemes through their algorithms in order to persuade users toward particular engagements with those systems.

work_title: Falling in love for all the right reasons: eHarmony, procedurality, and power
Falling in Love for All the Right Reasons: A Procedural Rhetorical Analysis of eHarmony.com
pages: Mass customization, one of the hallmarks of Web 2.0, uses computational processes that mirror human procedures of matching and categorization to personalize web applications for their users. As these processes continue to proliferate, it is important to understand the logics and cultural assumptions that empower them. To that end, this article examines the data preparation, matching, and communications workflows of online dating site eHarmony.com as a procedural rhetoric. It argues that the ideological perspective from which the site's functionality was developed creates a paternalistic relationship with its users that defines the subject positions and relationship formations made available to them.

Effects of Fit and Fall Proof ™ Program on PASE Scores with Older Adults
pages: Background: The purpose of the study was to examine the effects of a 12-week Fit and Fall Proof ™exercise program (45 minutes; two days per week) for older adults on physical activity levels. Method: Forty-nine community dwelling older adult volunteers, aged 64-95 (M=77.29 ±7.60), participated in the study. Baseline and ending PASE (Physical Activity Scale for the Elderly) scores were used to determine physical activity levels for the exercise (n=34) and control (n=15) groups. Results: One way ANOVA results reported no significant PASE score differences at baseline between the exercise (103.65 ±57.89) and control (113.74 ±58.30) groups. At the completion of the 12-week exercise program, no significant differences were found with the PASE scores between the exercise group (97.82 ±58.03) and control (91.20 ±51.76). Paired T-test analyses within each group demonstrated that the exercise group significantly increased PASE activities involving muscular strength and endurance (pre: 3.13 ±6.16; post:10.52 ±12.82) and decreased engagement in outdoor gardening (pre: 7.06 ±9.70; post: 2.94 ±7.19) by the end of the intervention. The control group reported a significantly lower final PASE score compared to baseline results. No significant correlations were reported between PASE scores and height, weight, BMI, modified Berg Balance Scale, timed 8-foot up-and-go, 30 second chair stand, and arm curl (p > 0.05). Conclusions: While the 12-week exercise program did not result in significantly higher levels of physical activity with the older adult exercise group, the program helped maintain a level of physical activity that was not found with participants in the control group.

Changing the Landscape for Multilingual Undergraduate Students: Faculty Reflections on Teaching Cross-Cultural Courses
Teaching for Agency: From Appreciating Linguistic Diversity to Empowering Student Writers
pages: NOTE: I'm not the first author, but DM seems to automatically populate these entries by assuming the Boise State faculty member will be the first author. In this article, we build on conversations about linguistic diversity in writing studies, proposing a framework by which instructors and administrators can promote the empowerment of multilingual writers. Our framework, which we call “teaching for agency,” recognizes the resources that linguistically diverse students bring to our writing classrooms, but also takes into account these students’ needs and goals regarding English language development. We articulate a process in which students gain greater awareness and control of the opportunities for action available to them, and learn to evaluate the effects of their decisions as writers and scholars. Practitioners can help to facilitate this process, we argue, by creating optimal conditions within which students can make informed decisions. After presenting the “teaching for agency” framework, we describe how we have employed it at our own institutions, through assignments that provide an authentic and relevant rhetorical context for student writing, as well as programmatic policies that offer multiple pathways for student success. By foregrounding agency as a central construct in the teaching of writing, we hope to demonstrate our respect for what students already know and can do with language, and our commitment to expanding every student’s linguistic and rhetorical repertoire.

Teaching clinical social work skills primarily online: An evaluation.
pages: This article describes an evaluation of the first skills-based clinical course taught in a Council on Social Work Education-accredited, entirely online, MSW program. Students in the online course answered retrospective pretest and posttest questions regarding change in their clinical skills. Researchers compared online students' responses to a standardized course evaluation with student responses on the face-to-face version of the same course. Online students reported significant increase in skills, and their final assignment and course evaluation scores were comparable to students in the face-to-face course, with the exception of instructor availability and facilitation of learning. Implications for teaching skills-based practice classes online are discussed.

work_title: Identifying ATT&CK Tactics in Android Malware Control Flow Graph Through Graph Representation Learning and Interpretability
pages: To mitigate a malware threat it is important to understand the malware's behavior. The MITRE ATT&ACK ontology specifies an enumeration of tactics, techniques, and procedures (TTP) that characterize malware. However, absent are automated procedures that would characterize, given the malware executable, which part of the execution flow is connected with a specific TTP. This paper is the first in providing an automation methodology to locate TTP in a sub-part of the control flow graph that describes the execution flow of a malware executable. This methodology merges graph representation learning and tools for machine learning explanation.

work_title: Marianne Moore and the Archives: From Material Culture to the Digital Humanities
pages: The essays that comprise Marianne Moore and the Archives: From Material Culture to the Digital Humanities use new archival research to explore the work of this major American modernist poet, providing innovative approaches to Moore’s career as it is documented in her archives. The volume represents new interpretations of archival materials found at the Rosenbach Museum and Library in Philadelphia, where Moore’s collection is held. This volume is also the first that draws upon the Marianne Moore Digital Archive (MMDA), a major project that is digitizing, transcribing, and annotating Moore’s notebooks for use by scholars, students, and non-academics to make these materials more widely accessible.

work_title: Implementing Process Oriented Guided Inquiry Learning (POGIL) in undergraduate biomechanics: Lessons learned by a novice
pages: Process Oriented Guided Inquiry Learning (POGIL) uses specially designed activities and cooperative learning to teach content and to actively engage students in inquiry, analytical thinking and teamwork. It has been used extensively in Chemistry education, but the use of POGIL is not well documented in other physical and biological sciences. This is a descriptive account of the initial implementation of POGIL in a university biomechanics course and includes the benefits, challenges and recommendations for teachers interested in using this effective instructional strategy.

Grandparental help in Indonesia is directed preferentially towards needier descendants: A potential confounder when exploring grandparental influences on child health
pages: A considerable body of evidence has now demonstrated positive correlations between grandparental presence and child health outcomes. It is typically assumed that such correlations exist because grandparental investment in their grandchildren improves child health and wellbeing. However, less is known about how grandparents allocate help to adult children and grandchildren, particularly in lower income contexts. Here we use detailed quantitative data from the longitudinal Indonesia Family Life Survey (data collected in 1993, 1997, 2000, 2007; n=16,250) to examine grandparental help in a society transitioning both demographically and economically. We test the hypothesis that grandparents direct help preferentially towards those adult children and grandchildren most in need of help. This hypothesis was supported for help provided by married grandparents and single grandmothers, who tended to: provide more help to their adult children when this generation had young children themselves, provide financial help if their adult children were poorer, and provide more household help if their adult daughters worked outside the home. One unexpected result was that help from maternal and paternal grandparents is positively correlated; if one set of grandparents is helping the other set is more likely to help, counter to our predictions. These results provide support for the hypothesis that grandparents preferentially invest in some descendants over others, where married grandparents and single grandmothers tend to invest in those adult children and grandchildren with the most need. Investigating the effect of grandparents on child health outcomes may therefore be confounded by grandparent’s preferential investment in needier descendants.

Tact and the Pedagogical Relation: Introductory Readings
pages: Tact and the Pedagogical Relation focuses on two topics of increasing interest both in teacher education and research. It shows how questions of sensitive and attuned action as well as educators’ relations with children and the young are special—uniquely different from other relations and attunements. This collection introduces readers to both classical and contemporary texts, offering many of these in translation for the first time. These illuminate the struggles and rewards of teaching, showing teaching to be an art, simultaneously a personal and professional calling. I am the editor and translator of this book; it includes multiple chapter introductions written by me.

Coil-to-Bridge Transitions of Self-Assembled Water Chains Observed in a Nanoscopic Meniscus
pages: Ten downward portions in the large oscillatory force-distance curve reported earlier are analyzed to understand a nanoscale water meniscus confined between a sharp probe and a flat substrate in air. The sigmoidal shape of each portion leads to assumption that the meniscus is made up of n independent transitions of two states, one for a coil state and the other for a bridge state, in each portion. The analysis reveals that each downward portion results from a coil-to-bridge transition of n self-assembled water chains whose length ranges between 197 and 383 chain units. The transition provides novel insights into water’s unique properties such as the high surface tension and the long-range condensation distance.

work_title: Making New World Publics: Botanical Studies in Sixteenth-Century Europe
pages: When Christopher Marlowe's Faustus sells his soul to the devil in exchange for all the knowledge in the world, he requests three books from Mephaestophilis: one on incantations, a second on new astronomy, and a third "wherein [he] might see all plants, herbs and trees that grow upon the earth". Evident in this last request is the importance of earth's botanical cornucopia to early modern Europe, a knowledge base that expanded exponentially with the encounter, exploration, and merchandising of the Americas.

work_title: Dynamic capabilities in sustainable supply chain management: An inter-temporal comparison the food and automotive industries
pages: This paper seeks to enrich the theoretical debate on dynamic capabilities (DCs) in sustainable supply chain management (SSCM). By extending Beske et al.’s (2014) study, a systematic literature review was conducted, and articles matching our inclusion criteria were analyzed from 2002 to 2018. Yet, two major additions are made. For the first time, two distinctive sectors, i.e., the food and automotive industry, are compared. Furthermore, a temporal perspective is provided by comparing two time periods (2002-2013 and 2014-2018) based on content as well as quantitative contingency analyses. The results for the food sector indicate a shift from “standards and certifications,” a central construct within the 2002-2013 sample, to proactive strategies aiming for the integration of stakeholders in the 2014-2018 sample. Similarly, the findings of the automotive industry indicate a shift from monitoring to joint development and knowledge management. Based on our comparison, the SSCM debate in the food industry appears more diverse in terms of practices and capabilities employed. In contrast, the analysis for the automotive industry indicates a focus on SCM elements instead of a comprehensive SSCM view. To the best of our knowledge, this is the first attempt to apply an intra- and inter-sectoral analysis combined with a temporal analysis within the SSCM domain. This provides evidence that the methodological approach taken allows distinguishing among both time periods and industries.

work_title: The application of theory in literature reviews - illustrated with examples from supply chain management
pages: Abstract Purpose - Literature review articles have become a frequently applied research approach in operations and supply chain management (SCM). The purpose of this paper aims to elaborate on four approaches for developing or employing theory in systematic literature reviews (SLRs). Design/methodology/approach - The paper uses conceptual arguments and illustrates them by pointing to recent examples. In SLRs, the material collection is usually based on keywords and searching databases, which is comparatively well documented. Data analysis, however, often falls short in documentation and, consequently, is neither well explained nor replicable. Therefore, the focus of this paper is the elaboration of the data analysis and sense-making stage in the research process of SLRs. Findings - The paper presents four different approaches, which are characterized as theory (1) building, (2) modification, (3) refinement and (4) extension, based on whether new concepts are formed or extant concepts within SCM or other fields of management theory are adopted. Research limitations/implications - The limitation of this research is that literature reviews could be conducted and presented in many ways. Since the focus of this research is on systematic literature reviews, only a limited number of approaches can be discussed and presented here. Originality/value - The paper contributes to explaining the process and expected outcomes of a literature review and, therefore, aids in further developing the related methodological approaches. This is relevant as literature review publications now often replace conceptual or theoretical pieces but still have to deliver concerning demands of theory building. Keywords Supply chain management, Systematic literature review, Theory development, Research process Paper type Research Paper

work_title: Data analytics in rail transportation: Applications and effects for sustainability
pages: Abstract—Advanced integrated technology and big data are current and growing industry concerns. We evaluate applications of big data analytics, especially with implications for sustainability, to rail transportation. We compare various findings to our exploratory case study. Data was collected from partners in a buyer-supplier relationship. The case considers one of the largest railroad network operators in North America and an Internet of Things (IoT) provider that supplies specialized sensors, digital video recorders, and hardware platforms. Practical managerial and organizational lessons are presented. Key words: Data analytics, logistics, rail transportation, sustainability

work_title: Creating action research and community-based learning opportunities in sustainable supply chain curriculum
pages: Abstract As businesses continue to face stakeholder pressure to adopt more sustainable and responsible practices, business schools must also adapt to changing demands and redesign curricula to include sustainability topics. This paper analyzes the use of community-based learning as an approach to integrating sustainability in supply chain management curriculum. To aid the development of such opportunities, the constructs of uncertainty and integration are presented with linkages to Bloom’s Taxonomy. Two cases of project development and implementation illustrate the potential learning outcomes and highlight challenges and risks one may expect before embarking on the journey to innovate pedagogical approaches. This paper aims to provide ideas and examples of ways to both enhance the learning experience for students while concurrently developing action research opportunities for educators and scholars. Keywords: sustainability, community-based learning, pedagogy, Operations, Supply Chain Management.

work_title: Linking sustainability-oriented innovation to supply chain relationship integration
pages: Sustainable strategies applied in the context of supply chain management are receiving increasing attention from practitioners and researchers. In this regard, innovation in products, organizational structures, and business methods can be the key to achieving economic, social, and environmental outcomes. The purpose of this paper is to analyze how sustainable-oriented innovations (SOI) can influence inter-organizational relationships in sustainable supply chain management. The research is based on two case studies of Brazilian focal companies (Braskem and Mercur) and their respective suppliers and customers. We have identified different realities regarding operational aspects, supply chain structure, and the strategic orientation for sustainability. The cases outlined provide in-depth insights into the forms of SOI, i.e. product and organizational innovations. A practical implication includes the illustration of how the sustainability innovations allow the reaping of positive effects to businesses along the supply chain. Collaborative relationships with suppliers and buyers can be seen as a source of learning, development of new technology processes, and information acquisition. We position our research within the realm of sustainable SCM as a contribution to the increasingly discussed relationship dimensions and present links to the sustainable innovation literature, which is rarely amalgamated with the SCM discipline. This establishes a more concrete connection, where further research at this intersection would be required.

The Echo of Pi'ilani's Story in W.S. Merwin's The Folding Cliffs
pages: W. S. Merwin’s 1998 volume The Folding Cliffs is a book-length narrative poem about the famous nineteenth-century Kauaians Pi‘ilani and her husband Ko‘olau. The poem tells how the couple kept their family intact by preventing the exile of Ko‘olau and the couple’s son Kaleimanu to the leper colony on the remote island of Moloka‘i. Merwin characterizes Pi‘ilani as the protagonist, partly by beginning his narrative after the deaths of the husband and son and focusing on Pi‘ilani’s memory of them, then circling back to present their story more fully. Toward the end of The Folding Cliffs, moreover, Merwin describes Pi‘ilani’s dictation of her story about her son and husband’s last days to the journalist John Sheldon. While this part of Merwin’s narrative poem records Sheldon’s documentation and revision of Pi‘ilani’s story about her husband’s leprosy and death, it also echoes and differs from Merwin’s own account of Ko‘olau’s last days, a story Merwin dramatizes in the preceding pages of his poem. In this self-reflexive scene of writing, Merwin invites his readers to speculate upon the similarities and differences between his poetic account of Pi‘ilani’s story and Sheldon’s version of it. Beyond that, this narrative doubling reveals Merwin’s awareness that his writing risks violating the integrity of Pi‘ilani’s experience just as much as Sheldon’s does. While Merwin accepts the impossibility of telling Pi‘ilani’s story more accurately than Sheldon did, he also forces his readers to recognize the autonomy of Pi‘ilani and her family by repeatedly expressing her sense that her story differs from Sheldon’s expectations about it. Paradoxically, Merwin’s readers experience Pi‘ilani most vividly through her sense of difference, but that difference also guarantees that she remains “other” to the reader. By portraying Pi‘ilani’s dictation of her story to John Sheldon, Merwin makes his readers keenly aware of Gayatri Chakravorty Spivak’s claim that “All speaking, even seemingly the most immediate, entails a distanced decipherment by another, which is, at best, an interception” (309). In focusing on the issues of “decipherment” and “interception” as she tells her story, Merwin underscores the irony and personal compromise of Pi‘ilani’s predicament. As a “native informant” (to use Spivak’s phrase), Pi‘ilani experiences the alienation entailed in the “interception” of her story by Sheldon. Since Pi‘ilani learns to read and write in The Folding Cliffs, Merwin implies that she could have written her own story instead of reporting it to Sheldon (though she would presumably have encountered difficulty in publishing it by herself). Merwin lets his readers see Sheldon’s sympathy at work as he records Pi‘ilani’s story, but he also invites them to recognize how Sheldon’s assumptions and concerns as a writer frame, and even skew, Pi‘ilani’s experience. At the same time, Merwin allows his readers to recognize his own dependency on Sheldon’s narrative for important details of Pi‘ilani’s story (a dependency he admits to when he describes his experience of reading Frances N. Frazier’s translation of Sheldon’s book in “How I Came to Write The Folding Cliffs”). In doing so, he invites his readers to honor Pi‘ilani as the source of her story, recognizing that because he offers only a version of it, they can admire its protagonist and sympathize with her without presuming to know or possess her story in a definitive (and hence totalizing) way.

Writing as Metamorphosis in Thylias Moss's Slave Moth
pages: In Slave Moth (2004), Thylias Moss emphasizes the way Varl Perry, her young female protagonist, uses writing to develop her understanding of freedom. As the author and narrator of her own story, Varl reacts to her master Peter Perry’s use of scientific discourse (including such key words as experiment and specimen) to characterize and control her (this discourse echoes Schoolteacher’s humiliating taxonomy in Toni Morrison’s Beloved). Although Varl’s literacy is an effect of her master’s experimentation, she uses this skill to imagine and frame her self-transformation from being someone else’s creature to becoming her own woman. Slave Moth emphasizes the positive cognitive impact of writing when Varl starts to record her thoughts by embroidering them into a series of petticoats she wears. In doing so, she materially and conceptually inhabits her writing. As her petticoat-diary grows, she increasingly associates it with the cocoon of the luna moth she reads about in her master’s open book. Through the ritual creation of the poem-as-cocoon, Varl exchanges her slave-mentality for a new independence of mind. She thereby reconceives the meaning of the name her master gave her (“Varl”) by contrasting it with the name her mother wanted to give her (“Free”) (Slave Moth 3 and 53).

"Cummings, Abbott and Costello: How "Who's on First?" Helps Students Understand "anyone lived in a pretty how town"
pages: Abstract for How “Who’s on First? ”Can Help Students Understand “anyone lived in a pretty how town” Listening to Abbott and Costello’s “Who’s On First?” can provide a helpful introduction to E. E. Cummings’s special use of pronouns in “anyone lived in a pretty how town.” Like Cummings, Abbott and Costello convert pronouns, other parts of speech, or short phrases into proper nouns. After students wrestle with this context in relation to the poem, they will be ready to think about other contexts, such as the legacy of Emersonian individualism or the Romantic idea of the child’s closeness to God. Finally, the role of gender in the love story is also worth exploring, and the romance between anyone and noone can be considered in the context of the ballad tradition.

Typification of Smittium, an Important Genus in the Taxonomy of Harpellales
Overview of 75 Years of Smittium Research, Establishing a New Genus for Smittium culisetae and Prospects for Future Revisions of the "Smittium" Clade
pages: The Harpellales includes 38 genera of endosymbiotic microfungi associated with various Arthropoda. Smittium, the second genus to be described, is now also the most species-rich of the order. Species of Smittium inhabit the digestive tracts of larval aquatic insects, especially lower Diptera, worldwide. During the 75 years since the type, Smittium arvernense, was described a number of advances in our understanding of the gut fungi have unfolded, in whole or in part, with Smittium as a model for the fungal trichomycetes. This in part relates to the high number of successful isolation attempts, with about 40% of known species having been cultured, a total number that far exceeds any other genus of gut fungus. Many isolates of Smittium have been used in laboratory studies for ultrastructural, physiological, host feeding, serological, as well as isozyme, and now ongoing molecular systematic studies. Previous and current molecular studies have shown that Smittium is polyphyletic but with consistent separation of Smittium culisetae, one of the most common and widespread species, from the remainder of Smittium species. A brief overview of Smittium research is provided. Zygospore and trichospore morphology and molecular evidence (immunological, isozyme, DNA sequences and phylogenetic analyses) are used to establish Zancudomyces and to accommodate Smittium culisetae. For the latter evidence, we include the first two-gene phylogenetic analysis, using combined 18S and 28S rRNA gene sequence data to show a cluster of Zancudomyces culisetae separate from Smittium. As the broadest taxon sampling of Smittium to date, this also serves a molecular systematic update toward revisionary syntheses of this and other Harpellales taxa.

work_title: Longitudinal monitoring of workloads in Women’s Division I (DI) Collegiate Basketball Across Four Training Periods
pages: Women's collegiate basketball is a fast-growing, dynamic sport that spans 8 or more months, with athletes competing in 30 + games in a season. The aim of this study was to quantify and profile the external load of practices and games during a Power-5 DI Women's Collegiate Basketball season. Specifically, Average PlayerLoad (PL), PlayerLoad per minute (PL*min −1 ), High Inertial Movement Analysis (High-IMA), and Jumps were quantified using Catapult Openfield software during four distinct training periods of the year: 8-hour preseason, 20-hour preseason, non-conference, and conference game play. Weekly variations and acute to chronic workload ratios (ACWR) were also examined. Eleven subjects participated in daily external load monitoring during practice and games via Catapult's ClearSky T6 inertial measurement units (IMU). Averages, standard deviations, and confidence intervals were calculated for training period comparisons, and Cohen's d was calculated as a measure of effect size. Findings include normative values to provide context for the demands experienced across an entire season. pages: Operation Street Sweeper (OSS) was a multi-level, interagency collaboration with multiple purposes. According to OSS documents, Operation Street Sweeper goals included the following: (1) to reduce gang-related criminal and violent activity in Nampa and Caldwell, Idaho through aggressive, proactive, and coordinated street enforcement between the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms (ATF) and local law enforcement; (2) to deter criminal activity through high profile enforcement activity; (3) to develop and/or increase the number of positive community contacts; (4) to show the community and gang members that law enforcement is serious about reducing gang and violent crime in the area; and (5) to use the media to showcase a law enforcement effort to reduce gang violence and activity.

work_title: Comparing local and proximal infrasound measurements at Mount Erebus, Antarctica: Implications for monitoring
pages: Proximal (10s - 100s of meters from vent) monitoring of volcanic infrasound is a common tool at volcanoes characterized by frequent low-magnitude eruptions, but it is generally not safe or practical to have sensors so close to the vent during more intense eruptions. To investigate the potential and limitations of monitoring at local ranges (1 to 10s of km) we studied infrasound detection and propagation at Mount Erebus, Antarctica. This site has both a good proximal monitoring network and an additional International Monitoring System infrasound array, IS55, located 25 km away. We compared data recorded at IS55 with a set of 117 Strombolian events that were recorded with the proximal array in January 2006. 75% of these events were identified at IS55 by an analyst looking for a pressure transient coincident with an F-statistic detection, which identifies coherent infrasound signals. With the data from January 2006, we developed and calibrated an automated signal-detection algorithm based on threshold values of both the F-statistic and the correlation coefficient. Application of the algorithm identified Strombolian signals at IS55 over the whole of 2006 and proved reliable for indicating trends in eruption frequency. However, detectability of signals at IS55 depended strongly on the proximal signal amplitude: 90% of events with proximal amplitudes > 25Pa were identified at IS55, compared to only 26% of events with proximal amplitudes <25Pa. Event detection was also affected by considerable variation in amplitude decay rates between the proximal and local sensors. Amplitudes recorded at IS55 varied between 2% and 74% of the amplitude expected assuming hemispherical spreading, indicating that amplitudes recorded at local ranges are unreliable indicators of event magnitude. Comparing amplitude decay rates with locally collected radiosonde data indicates a close relationship between recorded amplitude and lower atmosphere sound speed structure. At times of increased sound speed gradient, higher amplitude decay rates are observed, consistent with increased upward refraction of acoustic energy along the propagation path. This study indicates that whilst monitoring activity levels at local ranges can be successful, variable amplitude decay rate means quantitative analysis of infrasound data for eruption intensity and magnitude is not advisable without consideration of local atmospheric sound speed structure.

"Moving On," Men and the Changing Character of Interwar Working-Class Neighborhoods: From the Files of the Manchester and Liverpool City Police
pages: Investigations of complaints regarding police families made to the Manchester and Liverpool City Police provide insights into working-class neighborhoods not available in standard sources. The files suggest that interwar neighborhoods were losing long-term residents and becoming more diverse and variable. Families tried to find areas with similar standards regarding noise, space and privacy. Formerly stable neighborhoods changed, creating stress if changes were too dramatic. Even minor tensions could unsettle streets since causes of strain tended to reflect on respectability and status. While women remained the main presence due to their domestic responsibilities, men were spending more time with their families. The presence of men exacerbated misunderstandings, adding frictions over masculinity and territoriality. Complaints over noise overlapped with concerns over space which overlapped with anxiety over respectability and masculinity, all aggravated by children and gossip. When differences became too extreme, neighbors started campaigns of arguments, complaints, and harassment. Ultimately, if families were not in harmony with the rest of a street, efforts were made to force them to move. Yet neighborliness had not disappeared. Working-class neighbors generally managed to get along even in the unsettled conditions of interwar Liverpool and Manchester.

Great Powers in my Backyard: Frontline Ally Support for the U.S. Military
pages: How does public messaging affect public support for, or opposition to, a U.S. military presence abroad? This study focuses on Poland as a case of a frontline ally with an exceptionally high external security threat and a U.S. military presence. Using a pre-registered survey experiment, we explore how external security threats, economic gains, and the distance of a new military installation affect attitudes toward the U.S. military. Our results show that despite a substantial increase in support for the U.S. military presence since 2020, informational prompts about security threats and basing’s possible economic benefits do not increase public support for a new U.S. military base. Alternatively, the distance of a proposed military base seems to matter more, with respondents having a higher probability of expressing more support for a more distant military installation. Additional robustness tests reveal that previous individual contact with U.S. military personnel somewhat moderates that effect.

work_title: The Three Body Problem and International Relations
pages: The events across the Three Body Problem trilogy paint a realist universe where Trisolaris and Earth are engaged in a complex deterrence game surrounded by unknown other actors in a dark forest. However, by examining the behavior of the wallfacers and the choices of sub-global actors, domestic political explanations become necessary to understand the choices of Earth. Finally, we conclude with the dangers of a realist frame of galactic politics and how such framing makes omnicide more, not less, likely.

work_title: Efficacy of informationn extraction from bar, line, circular, bubble and radar graphs
pages: With the emergence of enormous amounts of data, numerous ways to visualize such data have been used. Bar, circular, line, radar and bubble graphs that are ubiquitous were investigated for their effectiveness. Fourteen participants performed four types of evaluations: between categories (cities), within categories (transport modes within a city), all categories, and a direct reading within a category from a graph. The representations were presented in random order and participants were asked to respond to sixteen questions to the best of their ability after visually scanning the related graph. There were two trials on two separate days for each participant. Eye movements were recorded using an eye tracker. Bar and line graphs show superiority over circular and radial graphs in effectiveness, efficiency, and perceived ease of use primarily due to eye saccades. The radar graph had the worst performance. “Vibration-type” fill pattern could be improved by adding colors and symbolic fills. Design guidelines are proposed for the effective representation of data so that the presentation and communication of information are effective.

Positioning faculty for funding at an emerging research institution: A case study to inform faculty academy programs.
pages: Emerging Research Institutions (ERIs), which generate less than $50 million in federal research funding, constitute one-third of all U.S. institutions of higher education (National Academy Press, 2009) and are notably one of the most impactful organizations in a state system for addressing social mobility, workforce development, and economic growth of a region (Birx, et. al., 2013). ERIs are often positioned to address issues of equity, diversity, and inclusion and faculty gain experience in working with first generation college students and diverse populations. Faculty at ERIs have immense opportunities to think creatively, develop scholarly projects, and establish partnerships that can generate high impact cultural, social, and economic advancements. Cultivating research at ERIs often requires that faculty expand skills sets extending beyond basic research to include broader impacts, innovation, social theory, multimedia, technology, career planning, project planning, and project management. One of the major essentials for building these skills is stepping out of the lab and practicing networked ideation, relationship building, and resource acquisition. Projects evolved through diverse networked ideation and disciplinary perspectives offer an enriched lens to maximize research quality and impacts. The skills mentioned are often a significant pivot in research and development thinking for academic faculty who are often intensely trained in lab infrastructures. Faculty often become siloed in like-minded, discipline specific networks. Faculty development infrastructure nested in a community of practice (CoP) can help transition the disciplinary and multidisciplinary silos into more robust interdisciplinary and transdisciplinary research teams, advancing artistry, research, and scholarship (ARS) from a new lens, networking many minds, with diverse perspectives (Leavy, 2016). There are no doubts that creative and innovative scholarship funding pursuits are necessary for emerging research institutions but often these pursuits can be a heavy lift, presenting faculty with challenges in setting up infrastructure, reliable partnerships, finding resources, and meeting promotion and tenure deadlines. Well-designed CoP for faculty development at emerging research institutions can serve to alleviate some of the heavy lift for faculty and coordinate more productive use of time, talents, and resources. The purpose of this study was to use a case study approach (Yin, 2018) to collect data on a cohort of faculty at an emerging research institution participating in a faculty academy aimed at positioning faculty for funding. The case study aims to inform an evolving faculty academy CoP by analyzing participants’ previous experiences with funding, attitudes about funding, resource needs, and behaviors working towards positioning for funding.

work_title: Building research capacity: Perspectives of early-stage investigators at an emerging research institution
pages: Early-stage investigators (ESI) have unique barriers to research success, but little is known about factors contributing to research success from the faculty perspective. Qualitative data from 10 faculty at an R2 institution in the southwestern United States were collected following participation in a Pilot Project Program (PPP) supported by the [BLINDED FOR REVIEW]. The major themes that emerged from qualitative analysis centered around institutional research culture (e.g., caliber and collegiality of faculty, teaching and students); and the common challenges and supports related to securing financial resources, accessibility and information from previous awardees and senior faculty, mentoring, grant writing support, administrative support, preliminary external reviews for grants, and identifying community collaborators. Our study reinforces that research culture, an institutional factor, is as important as individual facilitators and barriers for research development. If institutions are committed to transitioning from traditionally teaching focused universities to research intensive institutions, it is important to consider both institutional and individual factors that drive success in ESI. Future studies of research productivity among ESI should further examine how individual level factors interact with institutional factors to build research capacity.

work_title: The impact of college health and wellness courses on physical and mental health: A scoping review.
pages: Ninety percent of U.S. colleges and universities offer conceptually based fitness and wellness (CBFW) courses meant to improve students’ knowledge, and behavior relative to health, wellness and physical activity (PA). The purpose of this literature review was to investigate CBFW course content and structure, and review the effectiveness of courses or programs that sought to improve health and wellness perceptions and knowledge (HWP&K), physical health (PH), and mental health (MH). Twenty-three (23) articles, published in English between 2003 and 2023, met our inclusion criteria (n = 8059 subjects). The majority of courses (65%) focused on HWP&K and PH outcomes, with positive physical outcomes such as increased PA; some offered a physical activity lab component. Courses that focused on MH strategies (35%) improved MH outcomes such as reduced perceived stress. There is an opportunity for college courses to adopt strategies that will improve MH outcomes.

F.D.E. Schleiermacher’s Outlines of the Art of Education. A Translation and Discussion.
pages: "One must assume we are all familiar with what is commonly called ‘education.’" This is how Schleiermacher begins his famous 1826 lecture on the Art of Education . But in proceeding further―and unlike Rousseau or Locke before him―Schleiermacher carefully avoids assuming that education is primarily about a return to nature or about "soundness" of mind and body. Education is instead an ethical and political undertaking and a pragmatic art whose ultimate object and morality has differed greatly over time. It is exercised as a form of practical influence of the older generation on the younger: "A significant part of the activity of the older generation extends toward the younger," Schleiermacher reasons, and it "is more complete and perfect the more it is governed by an idea of what should happen―the more it has an exemplar to guide its action―the more it is an art . " This book offers these and other insights on education―long canonical in Central and Northern Europe―for the first time to an English audience. It also provides five chapters by scholars in education and its history that discuss various aspects of Schleiermacher’s lecture.

Navigating Changing Maps for Public Engagement in Higher Education Contexts
pages: Public engagement is becoming a critical element of US universities’ missions. Defining public engagement has become increasingly complex, however, and navigating the significant and diverse literature on public engagement can be daunting. This paper addresses this challenge as well as two others that make public engagement difficult for those feeling called (or pressured) to do such work. We draw on our own public engagement experience and research to 1) conceptually scope out the terrain of public engagement literature and approaches, 2) articulate how the emerging problems of rapid intensification and hyper-polarization in American political culture make public engagement work evermore challenging for both faculty and students, and 3) call attention to the ways in which universities are often not bureaucratically or structurally aligned to meaningfully support and advance public engagement work. We conclude with some recommendations for how faculty, staff, and administrators might navigate these concerns.

Archaeology in the Iwokrama Rainforest, Guyana
pages: The Iwokrama rainforest is a reserve of 371,000 hectares located in central Guyana (see Figure 1). Following its establishment in 1989, Williams (1996) conducted intuitive exploratory surveys of this little-known region and established a preliminary chronology of the reserve sites. These findings are complimented by recent investigations in the Iwokrama Mountains and along the Essequibo River (Plew 2002a, 2002b). Presently, archaeological data indicate significant Archaic and Horticultural occupations. A total of twenty-nine sites have been recorded. While no evidence of Paleo-Indians has been identified, it appears likely that evidence may come to light in the future, given what appears as a presence in Guyana and the Amazonian basin. It seems likely that Paleo-Indians utilizing the northern Rupununi would have intruded into the Iwokrama forest.
